# Cursor Setup Project

## Tools Installed
- Cursor IDE
- Git
- GitHub

## Steps Completed
1. Installed Cursor IDE
2. Installed Git
3. Initialized Git repository
4. Created README file

## Issues & Solutions

### Git not recognized
- Git was not installed
- Installed Git and restarted Cursor

### Claude Code not found
- Not available in Cursor
- Continued with built-in AI

### Codex not found
- Not available in marketplace
- Continued without it

## Conclusion
Successfully set up project and version control using Git and GitHub.
## Key Learnings

- Not all tools or extensions are always available, especially across different environments
- It's important to adapt and continue with available resources instead of getting blocked
- Basic Git setup is essential for any development workflow
- Cursor provides built-in AI capabilities that can replace external extensions in some cases

## Reflection

During this setup, I encountered missing extensions (Claude Code and Codex), which initially blocked progress. Instead of stopping, I investigated the limitations of Cursor's marketplace and continued using built-in features.

This experience reinforced the importance of adaptability and problem-solving when working with new tools or environments.